Justice Sandra Day O'Connor, the first woman on the Supreme Court, was admired for her commitment to the stable center, pragmatism, and search for common ground. Despite not agreeing with all her opinions, her decency, devotion to the facts, and active citizenship were respected. Overcoming discrimination early in her career, she dedicated her life to public service and held elected office. She sought to avoid ideology and was devoted to the rule of law and an independent judiciary. Throughout her tenure, she remained open to learning, change, and understanding the real impact of the law on people's lives. Her historic nomination to the Supreme Court received overwhelming support from the Senate, demonstrating the nation's ability to come together. Justice O'Connor's advocacy for civic education and civil discourse has had a significant impact, emphasizing the importance of listening to one another and finding common ground as Americans.